pr_title: gpio: adds basic digital i/o support
pr_body:
* Map gpios as D1,2,etc to their gpionum and pinNum as per arduino_nano_r3_connector.dtsi
* pulldown i/p mode gpio by default
* implements pinMode, digitalRead, Write, delay and delayMicroseconds
* Includes examples for push button LED and blink LED and hello world
* For a comprehensive commit history on GPIO refer: https://github.com/DhruvaG2000/Arduino-Core-Zephyr/pull/4

Signed-off-by: Dhruva Gole <goledhruva@gmail.com>
pr_commits: [{'commit_sha': 'ba84fd87208fef82fe0330f90f4b7a02b1270f0a', 'committer_username': 'DhruvaG2000', 'committer_name': 'Dhruva Gole', 'committer_email': None, 'commit_date': datetime.datetime(2018, 7, 14, 12, 14, 17, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc)}, {'commit_sha': 'd950492e1cd78ed34d581719208fa178ef7a2656', 'committer_username': 'DhruvaG2000', 'committer_name': 'Dhruva Gole', 'committer_email': None, 'commit_date': datetime.datetime(2018, 7, 14, 12, 14, 17, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc)}]

```', 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2022, 7, 25, 18, 20, 1, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'szczys', 'type': 'User'}, {'comment_id': 929174385, 'comment_body': 'I will definitely look into this and change the MACROs accordingly.. thanks for this insight!', 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2022, 7, 25, 18, 23, 41, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'DhruvaG2000', 'type': 'User'}, {'comment_id': 933740952, 'comment_body': 'If `INPUT_PULLDOWN` is selected, how are pulldowns activated? Do we assume that the pull-down flag has already been set in the overlay file, or is there some other mechanism?', 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2022, 7, 30, 4, 52, 17, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'szczys', 'type': 'User'}, {'comment_id': 933743264, 'comment_body': 'I have not found a better way to do this, but it should be documented to help users who receive errors because they did not install in `/home/user/zerphyproject`', 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2022, 7, 30, 4, 56, 15, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'szczys', 'type': 'User'}, {'comment_id': 933756215, 'comment_body': "Not sure at this point what ``INPUT_PULLDOWN`` does in zephyr, I thought it was  a flag to make the gpio low state by default so it wouldn't have a floating value, but I think simple `INPUT` shud work as they have done here: https://github.com/zephyrproject-rtos/zephyr/blob/main/samples/basic/button/src/main.c#L51", 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2022, 7, 30, 5, 34, 36, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'DhruvaG2000', 'type': 'User'}, {'comment_id': 933757065, 'comment_body': "> Do we assume that the pull-down flag has already been set in the overlay file, or is there some other mechanism?

I am not sure how GPIO_ACTIVE_LOW works underneath, if it does some DT Stuff or not...
But here's a useful line from the docs:

> Interrupts sensitive to pin logical level take into account GPIO_ACTIVE_LOW flag. If a pin was configured as Active Low, physical level low will be considered as logical level 1 (an active state), physical level high will be considered as logical level 0 (an inactive state).

My understanding was it would be better to set the pin `ACTIVE LOW` than leave it floating because I was not sure what or if zephyr has some default pull down in it.", 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2022, 7, 30, 5, 44, 38, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'DhruvaG2000', 'type': 'User'}, {'comment_id': 933757077, 'comment_body': 'will add documentation for this in README as well as my blog', 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2022, 7, 30, 5, 45, 3, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'DhruvaG2000', 'type': 'User'}, {'comment_id': 933758125, 'comment_body': 'The `GPIO_ACTIVE_LOW` is an abstraction. Setting a pin to `HIGH` in your C code will turn that pin to the active level. Devicetree determines if that `HIGH` actually means voltage or ground based on `GPIO_ACTIVE_HIGH` or `GPIO_ACTIVE_LOW`. I think we should assume that the correct active level is set in the Devicetree.

There is a flag for pull-down resistors. So if the Arduino app wants to set a pull-down resistor, in Zephyr we should add the `GPIO_PULL_DOWN` flag when initializing the pin. https://docs.zephyrproject.org/latest/hardware/peripherals/gpio.html#c.GPIO_PULL_DOWN', 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2022, 7, 30, 5, 57, 45, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'szczys', 'type': 'User'}, {'comment_id': 933758772, 'comment_body': "Now I'm rethinking the topic of active level. I wonder if all GPIO pins should be set as active high? That way a `digitalWrite(pinNum, 1);` would drive the pin high. And for inputs, a V+ would be read as a 1 and ground as a 0. What are your thoughts?", 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2022, 7, 30, 6, 5, 39, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'szczys', 'type': 'User'}, {'comment_id': 933766634, 'comment_body': '> I wonder if all GPIO pins should be set as active high

Yes, I think this would be the right thing to do ', 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2022, 7, 30, 7, 30, 33, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'DhruvaG2000', 'type': 'User'}, {'comment_id': 933770709, 'comment_body': 'Check https://github.com/zephyrproject-rtos/gsoc-2022-arduino-core/pull/17/commits/044b45912185c7559470bc0f6114fda9dfc6b51e 

I tested on my arduino with this commit, button and blink led works perfect!', 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2022, 7, 30, 8, 10, 3, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'DhruvaG2000', 'type': 'User'}, {'comment_id': 933770736, 'comment_body': 'Done in README: https://github.com/zephyrproject-rtos/gsoc-2022-arduino-core/pull/17/commits/93deab35624d39d0688c202b8e348a06a018e912', 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2022, 7, 30, 8, 10, 21, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'DhruvaG2000', 'type': 'User'}, {'comment_id': 934007587, 'comment_body': '```suggestion
* **Pre requisites:** It is assumed that you have zephyrproject configured and installed on your system as per the official [Get Started Guide](https://docs.zephyrproject.org/latest/develop/getting_started/index.html). The recommended path to install is `~/zephyrproject` as specified in the guide. If you have zephyr installed in a custom path you may need to make changes to the CMakeLists.txt file in the sample code directory when building these samples.
```', 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2022, 7, 31, 16, 7, 28, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'szczys', 'type': 'User'}, {'comment_id': 934007906, 'comment_body': '```suggestion
* While compiling with the ArduinoCore-API `WCharacter.h` produces many errors. The include of that file needs to be deleted from `cores/arduino/api/ArduinoAPI.h` (it is unused in this port.) We are looking into resolving the issue.
', 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2022, 7, 31, 16, 10, 17, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'szczys', 'type': 'User'}, {'comment_id': 934009090, 'comment_body': "We're almost there. I suggest these changes: 

```suggestion
void pinMode(pin_size_t pinNumber, PinMode pinMode) {
  if (pinMode == INPUT) { // input mode
    gpio_pin_configure_dt(arduino_pins[pinNumber],
                          GPIO_INPUT | GPIO_ACTIVE_HIGH);
  } else if (pinMode == INPUT_PULLUP) { // input with internal pull-up
    gpio_pin_configure_dt(arduino_pins[pinNumber],
                          GPIO_INPUT | GPIO_PULL_UP | GPIO_ACTIVE_HIGH);
  } else if (pinMode == INPUT_PULLDOWN) { // input with internal pull-down
    gpio_pin_configure_dt(arduino_pins[pinNumber],
                          GPIO_INPUT | GPIO_PULL_DOWN | GPIO_ACTIVE_HIGH);
  } else if (pinMode == OUTPUT) { // output mode
    gpio_pin_configure_dt(arduino_pins[pinNumber],
                          GPIO_OUTPUT_LOW | GPIO_PULL_DOWN | GPIO_ACTIVE_HIGH);
  }
}
```
The reason for this is that the user should have the option of using their own external pull-up/pull-down resistor so we should not set the pull-down resistor by default, but only if the user code directs us to do so using the `INPUT_PULLDOWN` when setting pinmode.

Also, it is probably the same thing, but instead of defaulting to setting the pin as an output, we should test to make sure that's what the user asked for. 
", 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2022, 7, 31, 16, 19, 53, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'szczys', 'type': 'User'}, {'comment_id': 934009531, 'comment_body': "Oops, looks like I missed the boat on this one. I'll open a PR with these changes. Thanks!", 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2022, 7, 31, 16, 23, 45, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'szczys', 'type': 'User'}, {'comment_id': 934009798, 'comment_body': 'Yes I agree with these suggestions.', 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2022, 7, 31, 16, 25, 58, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'DhruvaG2000', 'type': 'User'}, {'comment_id': 934009953, 'comment_body': "I am thinking we'll make a seperate PR to update the README's of all the samples.
Currently they are just ditto copy pasted from the zephyr samples so may not make much sense.
But we could also leave this as a `good-beginner-task` to perhaps attract potential contributors.", 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2022, 7, 31, 16, 27, 5, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'DhruvaG2000', 'type': 'User'}]

pr_body:
This PR Adds a multi threading example to concurrently blink 3 LEDs.
This implements suggestions made by @szczys in https://github.com/zephyrproject-rtos/gsoc-2022-arduino-core/pull/13

[{'comment_id': 960976311, 'comment_body': "```suggestion
Arduino Core API module for zephyr leverages the power of Zephyr under an Arduino-C++ style abtraction layer thus helping zephyr new-comers to start using it without worrying about learning about new APIs and libraries. See the project documentation folder for detailed documentation on these topics:

* [Using external Arduino Libraries](/documentation/arduino_libs.md)
* [Adding board variantks](/documentation/overlays.md)
* [Adding custom boards](/documentation/variants.md)
```

The documentation folder doesn't have a README.md which means linking to it won't render a page. This might be a confusing user experience so I suggest linking explicitly to the available pages.", 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2022, 9, 1, 18, 24, 9, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'szczys', 'type': 'User'}, {'comment_id': 960985242, 'comment_body': '```suggestion

```

I think CMakeLists and variants.h should be shown in this tree view.', 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2022, 9, 1, 18, 49, 59, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'szczys', 'type': 'User'}, {'comment_id': 960998507, 'comment_body': 'This is confusing. pr_body:
Need help with println

Signed-off-by: Dhruva Gole <goledhruva@gmail.com>

[{'comment_id': 954252089, 'comment_body': '`println` should not have a newline at the beginning. This way you can do printf-like things on the same line:

```
Serial.print("Here is a number: ");
Serial.println(someNumber);
```
', 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2022, 8, 24, 20, 2, 54, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'szczys', 'type': 'User'}, {'comment_id': 954253776, 'comment_body': 'There should be a `print(const char* ptr)` version of this function.', 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2022, 8, 24, 20, 5, 3, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'szczys', 'type': 'User'}, {'comment_id': 954257598, 'comment_body': 'Functions should return the size_t for the number of bytes written.', 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2022, 8, 24, 20, 10, 15, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'szczys', 'type': 'User'}, {'comment_id': 955211577, 'comment_body': '```suggestion
    printk(lf ? "%s\n" : "%s", ptr);
```

I have made an error here. This should be `printk`, not `printf`.
', 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2022, 8, 25, 16, 52, 55, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'szczys', 'type': 'User'}, {'comment_id': 955214355, 'comment_body': '```suggestion
    printk("\n");
```

pr_body:
This variant is capable of printing numbers and according to the base parameter.
    For eg. Serial.print(78, DEC) will print the decimal equivalent of 78 and
    Serial.print(78, HEX)  will print HEX and so on.

Solves https://github.com/zephyrproject-rtos/gsoc-2022-arduino-core/issues/38

pr_body:
* Fixes https://github.com/zephyrproject-rtos/gsoc-2022-arduino-core/issues/40
* yield(): causes the current thread to yield execution to another thread of the same or higher priority.
If there are no other ready threads of the same or higher priority, the routine returns immediately.
* Also replace include Arduino "" with <>.

Signed-off-by: Dhruva Gole <goledhruva@gmail.com>
